node.text:
Jaisalmer • I’ve never posted a video here before but going through the photos of our time in Jaisalmer I was struck, just as I was in person, by this Rajasthani man’s song and had to share. He was sitting inside the fort at Jaisalmer playing for tips. It left me wondering about his life. Who he is, where he came from and what his story is. I bet he could talk for hours!
.
.
➡️Do you ever tip musicians on the street? 🎻🎵 ➡️What do you think of his tune?
.
.
I never paid much attention to street performers until my son came along. He is always so entranced by them, he even talked of being a busker in London’s underground during our visit there, that now I always pay special attention to them. .
.
.
.
.

node.text:
✨Highs & Lows of 2021 ✨

Another pandemic year, but this one with some really great experiences.

1️⃣ Continued homeschooling Cian on my own. This is not always easy, but every day I see the benefits of him being able to follow his interests and learn at his pace. It has been a much easier homeschool journey this year than in years past.

2️⃣ I backpacked over 95 miles this year with Cian on my own. Often considered for ‘the boys’, I rocked it. There were moments I felt nervous, unsure of myself and wondered if I could really do it, but I did it. Not only did we do regular backpacking trips, but we also completed 2 thru hikes on the JMT &  took 2 friends backpacking. 

3️⃣ Camping. We spent 30 nights camping this year. I really honed in on my solo camping skills. Usually we camp with friends but for much of this year we were on our own, which was actually really awesome.

4️⃣ Hiked and biked 700 miles. We had a goal to hike and bike 1000 miles,  but as life began to open up more, we lost our way. But hey. I’m not complaining, 700 miles is still pretty amazing. That’s more than 50 miles a month! 

5️⃣ Getting to visit Saudi Arabia was such a special adventure especially after so long without international travel. 

6️⃣ Finally taking Cian to the Grand Tetons and Yellowstone was such a highlight of the year. Doing a photography tour with him was really special. 

👎 The low points: 

 - I feel like we lost a close connection with some formerly good friends. I know friendships wax and wane, but this one continues to hang over my heart. 

 - My dad has been very ill all year but I’ve not made it to Texas to see him. I really wish I would have made more of a priority to get there once we were all vaccinated. 

- I didn’t spend as much time as I would have liked on my blog. I really struggle with time management being a homeschool parent and working from home. And I get super down on myself for not being better at it. 

There are many more high and lows, but I’m out of space! How was your year? 

Next up.. goals and dreams for 2022. 

#grandtetons #grandtetonnationalpark #wyoming #explorewyoming #nationalpark #nationalparkgeek #nationalparkobsessed #findyourpark

node.text:
🚗 Day trip to Sharaan Nature Reserve

I can’t stop thinking of our visit to Saudi. It was such a special trip, filled with lovely people, beautiful scenery and delicious food. 

As I’ve mentioned, AlUla was one of our favorite places on our quick trip.

When we were in AlUla, we took a vintage jeep safari in the Sharaan Reserve. Our visit was a little different than @pangaeaclub’s regular tours, but it really gave us insight into the area and plenty of adrenaline fueled fun. 

We started off our adventure in the dark in an open air vintage jeep, heading deep into the reserve through sand dunes and sandstone rocks all around us. We stopped at the area pictured for sunrise before heading to a popular spot known as Dancing Rocks. It was such a beautiful morning exploring the reserve all on our own as you can only visit through a tour! 

If you are heading to AlUla, consider taking a day trip out to the desert area to explore more. 

Now.. how to stop myself dreaming of a Saudi return…

node.text:
🐪 AlUla Old Town 

One of our favorite places that we visited in Saudi was the Old Town of AlUla. While much of the fun of this tourist hot spot is out in the desert we really enjoyed strolling the streets of this cute area. 

If you are planning to visit AlUla, you must have lunch at the Pink Camel. I ate the most delicious halloumi and avocado sandwich there with my favorite drink, a frozen mint lemonade. 

After lunch, head across the road to the Old Town for a little shopping. Here there are cafes, outdoor dining areas, a Dunkin’ Donuts (of course), an oud shop, a workshop demonstrating traditional weaving and even a few tourist shops. 

This was the only place we found in Saudi that had a distinctively tourist feel, but in a very well done, tasteful way.

Other items on my must do list here in AlUla include:

🐘 Hanging out at Elephant Rock at sunset

👣 Walking the Dadan Trail of Old Town

🛻 Desert adventure in vintage jeeps
 
📷 Take photos at the mirror cube, Maraya 

🏨 Stay at Shaden Desert Resort which is an insanely beautiful property! 

We didn’t have time to visit a few other spots, so I know we will have to visit again!

node.text:
✨Dune Bashing ✨

Have you heard of dune bashing? We had been in dune buggies like this one pictured before on the coast of California, but we had never been dune bashing in a car before. It was so fun and one of my sons’s highlights of the trip. 

A morning spent in the Red Sands area outside of Riyadh included a mobile coffee stand, sand boarding, dune bashing and riding around in dune buggies. It was definitely an adventure worth planning for if you visit Riyadh. 

🐪 What’s your ideal desert excursion - riding camels or dune bashing2buggies?

node.text:
“A sea of black abayas and white thobes. Red and white keffiyeh. The calm quiet of an Arabian sunrise. The whistling of the sand as it blows over. The ever present smell of oud permeating my clothes and hair. The welcoming hellos from strangers eager to share their stories of travel to the US.”

🇸🇦 This is Saudi. Welcome my friends to a land ready for tourists. What are you waiting for? 

An excerpt from my journal is apparently a personal ad for Saudi 🤣. 

❤️ This country has taken hold of my heart. And Cian’s too. Out of 35 countries he says Saudi made it to the top 10, number 7 to be exact. 

If you ask why, all I can say is that it is mesmerizing. The people are so welcoming. It’s raw, but refined. 

The sunsets. The sunrises. The hospitality. The friendliness. The smiles. The smell of oud.

Is Saudi what you expected?

node.text:
🎉 Riyadh Season Festival 

For the second year, Riyadh Season festival is happening. After a break due to the pandemic it is back bigger than ever. Throughout Riyadh there are amazing temporary exhibition spaces with venues for entertainment, concerts, amusement parks and so much more. 

We were told that coming to Riyadh and not going to a Riyadh Season event is like not visiting the city at all! This is where you will be able to dive in with locals to get the full experience of the city.

There are literally hundreds of events, so we could only sample a few. 

🦒 Riyadh Safari Park - located well outside the city, this safari park takes guests in monster truck safari jeeps around the enclosures to see mostly African animals roaming around. It was pretty cool to see a golden tiger and a liger! 

🚙 Riyadh Car Show - includes a racetrack for car tricks, falcons to hold, traditional song/dance performances and of course cars cars cars! 

❄️ Winter Wonderland - a winter themed amusement park located right in the city with delicious food stalls, shopping and tons of fun rides. 

⭐️ The Boulevard - our favorite of the ones we visited included cool light and water installations, world themed areas with pop up restaurants and entertainment from around the world. One to revisit multiple times! 

+ A must visit🌵The Museum of Happiness - a center for families with cute photo opportunities and hands on ways to achieve a moment of happiness. It was so fun! Ice cream, bike powered lemonade & diving in a marshmallow pool just to get you started!

🇸🇦See my stories and Saudi highlight to check them all out in more detail. 

➡️ When you travel do you seek out local festivals? What have been some of your favorite local festivals?

node.text:
🇸🇦Welcome to Saudi!

Cian and I are in Saudi for the week, exploring family friendly sights in the capitol Riyadh and beyond. 

Saudi opened to tourism in 2019, but quickly shut again due to the pandemic. The country is now back open for fully vaccinated travelers (kids under 12 are exempt). 

It is very different than I thought it would be. It is not as hot as I imagined - it’s been absolutely beautiful weather so far, much like LA.

The dress code is much more relaxed than I imagined it would be. The abaya is still common as is the thobe for men, but is not required for locals or foreigners. It is not totally unheard of to see women wearing jeans.

On our first day, we went abaya shopping. I figured why not join the local culture and wear one! Swipe through to see me with it on!

We also visited the Al-Masmak Fort where the origins of the present city of Riyadh started in 1902. There is so much to learn about this city and we are just scratching the surface. 

Riyadh is a bustling, modern place with pockets of old style peeking through. We are excited to keep exploring. 

Do you have questions about Saudi or Riyadh in particular? Let me know what all you would like to see or know more about while I’m here.

node.text:
🐑 Wool Obsessed 

It all started with a dress and a challenge from @wool.and. What was my effort to purchase my first piece in a capsule wardrobe ended up fueling an obsession that has taken hold this past year. For me, 2021 was the year I truly discovered merino wool! 

This photo was not a planned or sponsored photo - just a regular day out hiking for us. But here we are wearing almost head to toe wool! We really do love it, which is why I always talk about it! 

I try not to buy into the frenzy of Black Friday shopping, but wool is not cheap, so the best time to purchase it is when companies are having sales! 💰

And since all my favorite woolies are having sales right now, and so many of you have asked about our wool clothes, here are our favorites —- 

👗 What I am wearing: 

@wool.and dress
@comradsocks my favorite wool compression socks 
@branwynofficial is hidden underneath - my undies 
@woolxwool is what I typically wear for leggings but they don’t have blue yet! 

👧 Cian has on his blue @letsgoiksplor long sleeve thermal with @nuiorganics short sleeve on top. 

I wrote up a post on why you should all consider merino wool for your clothes, which is linked in my bio. To recap - it’s environmentally friendly, it wears well, doesn’t need washing often, repels odors and keeps you comfortable no matter the weather. 

To read more about merino wool and all the brands I recommend, head to my profile for the link. 

🚨PSA: When you are shopping this holiday season, please try to use affiliate links when you can. It makes no difference to your final cost, but can really add up for small businesses like myself. 

Have you tried merino wool? Are you ready to jump on the wool bandwagon with me?

node.text:
✨Sequoia and Kings Canyon Fundraiser ✨⁣
⁣
If you followed us this past year you will know how much we love @sequoiakingsnps. These two parks became our home away from home during COVID. We were able to renew ourselves there hiking, snowshoeing and camping. ⁣
⁣
One of the best backpacking trails there, the Rae Lakes Loop is what inspired us to get in gear for backpacking. It was our hope to do it in the fall, but then came the massive fires that took over the park. ⁣
⁣
Now we can do it virtually in an effort to raise funds to help the @sequoiaparksconservancy, who will be tasked with rebuilding and repairing after this years devastating wildfires. ⁣
⁣
Please consider donating to this great cause and showing your support for Cian in his first self initiated fundraiser! ⁣
⁣
This was all Cian’s idea and I’m fully on board. We love these California parks and hope that we are able to get back out there soon! ⁣
⁣
We have to hike 41 miles this month. We are more than half way through the month but still have quite a bit of our miles to go!! ⁣Can we do it?
⁣
Cian has a goal of raising $500, but we aren’t quite there.. any little bit you can give would be awesome for his confidence in fundraising and for our favorite parks! ⁣
⁣
We will be hitting the trails this weekend, so if you are in LA and want to join us for a hike, let us know! ⁣
⁣
Clickable link to donate is in my stories and saved on my Sequoia highlight reel. https://runsignup.com/ciantravels⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
🚂 Welcome to the Suisun Valley ⁣
⁣
I’m sure that many of you have never heard of the Suisun Valley. Before our trip I didn’t really know much either. But I will tell you, your kids will ❤️ it. And so will you 🍷! ⁣
⁣
Located in the North Bay area between San Francisco and Sacramento, the main town here is well known for its candy factory. (Swipe to see which one!)⁣
⁣
In adult circles it’s also becoming more known for its family owned vineyards. ⁣
⁣
If you are in the Bay Area looking for something to do, we highly recommend a visit up to Fairfield and the Suisun Valley. ⁣
⁣
Our top picks for a family visit: ⁣
⁣
🍬 Take a self guided tour of the @jellybellycandyco factory. Any guesses how much candy we came out of there with?⁣
⁣
🚗 Explore the Suisun Valley vineyards and farming area with stops at @larrysproduce, Cal Yee Farms, and @woodenvalleywinery ⁣
⁣
🚂 Take a ride on a vintage train at the @westernrailwaymuseum. This is especially fun during the Halloween and Christmas seasons. ⁣
⁣
🥘 Grab some food (and beers) at the @rustwater_taproom or breakfast at the Joy of Eating Cafe. ⁣
⁣
🐴 It you happen to be in town on the 3rd Sat of the month, hop over to Rush Ranch @solanolandtrust for arts, crafts, blacksmith demos and nature hikes.⁣
⁣
⁣
⚫️ Save this post for your next visit! ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
✨East Bay Weekend Retreat ✨⁣
⁣
After a few days at Pinnacles, we headed to the Bay Area to revisit my old stomping grounds in the Tri-Valley. This area is considered Pleasanton, Dublin, Livermore and the town of Danville. My cousins lived here for the many years I lived in SF so I spent a lot of time out this way... But I’ve never spent time in the area exploring as a tourist with Cian. ⁣
⁣
🥳 When the Tri-Valley invited us up for the weekend, we jumped at the chance! ⁣
⁣
This area sits only 35 miles from San Francisco, but often feels worlds away. Vineyards, 🍷 tasting, gourmet restaurants and beautiful nature escapes are all waiting. ⁣
⁣
Our top picks:⁣
⁣
🏨 There are tons of places to stay, but we loved the @achotelpleasanton. Modern rooms conveniently located near the major parts of town. ⁣
⁣
🥗 Too many options, but our favorites were- @revelkitchenandbar in downtown Danville and 🥟 at Mayflower in Dublin. ⁣
⁣
🍦A MUST visit - @meadowlarkdairy - the best orange crush soft serve ice cream you will ever find! ⁣
⁣
👀 The @blackhawkmuseum was AMAZING! A former car museum now has a US history exhibit with a massive diorama, has an exhibit on China, the worlds animals & more. Really blown away by it! ⁣
⁣
🥾My favorite of course was hiking at Mt Diablo. For kids, Rock City is a must (pictured).⁣
⁣
Check out my stories for the next three days to see what all we got up to! ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
🌲Pinnacles National Park ⛰⁣
⁣
One of the least visited national parks in California and the last on our to do list. ⁣
⁣
This small park is a fun weekend trip for those in California and a must visit for bird lovers. ⁣
⁣
Home to the California condor, Townsend big eared bats and many other species, this park is a hit for wildlife lovers. ⁣
⁣
While this small park isn’t the easiest place to get to or stay, it is well worth the effort! ⁣
⁣
Top Things To Do: ⁣
🥾Hike Moses Spring Trail to Bear Gulch Reservoir ⁣
🚶Experience a talus cave (Bear Gulch is our favorite)⁣
🦇 Search for a big eared bat ⁣
🦅 Watch a California condor soar overhead ⁣
⁣
🏕: There is only 1 campground on the park, located on the east side. There are cabins, tent sites and RV sites here.⁣
⁣
⏰ The best time to visit is in the cooler months and when the caves are open. ⁣
⁣
📍 There are two entrances - one on the east and on the west. The roads do not connect. The campground and many popular trails are on the East. ⁣
⁣
🍲Bring plenty of food and snacks as the one small shop is quite limited in their selection. Water refill stations are available at a few trailheads. ⁣
⁣
🔦 Make sure to bring a headlamp or flashlight for exploring the caves. ⁣
⁣
✨ Is Pinnacles on your wish list? ⁣
